comments.body: Deployed to staging - waiting for feedback from Minjie Chen

_(1) https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99105697413506421_
Looks great!

_(2) https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/9946897643506421 (we wondered if not including the "Indigenous Studies" heading on this one is correct?)_
Aww this gets into the weed of cataloging rules. In this bib record, the subject heading of intererst is the following:

> White people—Canada—Relations with Indians—History

The LCSH string in LC's database, in contrast, is **White people—Relations with Indians** 
Now LC indicates that it's not allowed to attach geographical subdivision after the string. (Why? If I knew I guess I'd be working at LC...)
To get around the restriction, catalogers who wish to provide finer detail insert the geographical marker in between "White people" and "Relations with Indians," meaning such records would slip out of our left-match mechanism. My estimate is that the tagging would miss up to half of the bibs (around 200) with "Relations with Indians" in them due to the insertion. The number may be smaller if the bib contains other 650 that left-match other LC strings. See these examples I found in the bibs:

> $aWhite people--$zAlabama--$xRelations with Indians
> $aWhite people--$zCanada--$xRelations with Indians
> $aBlack people--$zCaribbean Area--$xRelations with Indians.
> $aBlack people--$zGeorgia--$xRelations with Indians.
> 
> $aWhites--$xSources.--$y19th century--$xRelations with Indians
> $aAfrican Americans--$zFlorida--$zFranklin County--$xRelations with Indians.
> $aWhite people--$zIllinois--$zChicago--$xRelations with Indians.
> $aWhite people--$zOntario--$zRainy River (District)--$xRelations with Indians.
> 

There are two options for you to consider.
First, stick with left matching and live with the (small) losses.

Second, use a seperate matching mechanism. Note that there is a second sheet named [Additional subfields](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jFsLExGilXWmXEikliuYUtdipF5HnRbNMZn-rgJYflY/edit#gid=1600276075) in the vocabulary list.

> ǂx Indian authors
> ǂx Indian influences
> ǂx Indian interpretations
> ǂx Indian languages
> ...


The presence of these topical divisions alone is suffcient to determing the relevance of the bibs to Indigenous Studies--unlike other subdivisions we talked about at our meeting on 05/27 and which Carolyn listed on [a page](https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/compare/what-to-remove-augment?expand=1#diff-ef2847b31f19f0c655e4cc5e4a332f3f94d6cca8aaec0987c4af1f8ff655dc31R169) linked above.

Would you be able to catch these subdivisions alone? Left-match from the start of the 650 field doesn't apply here, but the subfield x in bibs does need to match the terms in their entirety. For example, the first one is "ǂx Indian authors".  If a bib contains "ǂx **East** Indian authors" in 650, then it is not a match.

_(3) https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/997737533506421 (did not previously have heading, now does)_
Looks great!
Thanks!

In replying to @maxkadel's Slack message -

> an updated version for Augment the Subject has been deployed to catalog-staging. We've only indexed a few example records.For example:
> •	https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99105697413506421
> •	https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/9946897643506421 (we wondered if not including the "Indigenous Studies" heading on this one is correct?)
> •	https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/997737533506421 (did not previously have heading, now does)
> Let us know how it looks, and if there are any other examples from the catalog you would like us to test.
>

There is a fourth issue I'd like to bring about. I just realize that LC revised the following two terms this year --
<html xmlns:v="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:vml"
xmlns:o="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office"
xmlns:x="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:excel"
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40">

<head>

<meta name=ProgId content=Excel.Sheet>
<meta name=Generator content="Microsoft Excel 15">
<link id=Main-File rel=Main-File
href="file:///C:/Users/minjiec/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip.htm">
<link rel=File-List
href="file:///C:/Users/minjiec/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml">

</head>

<body link="#0563C1" vlink="#954F72">

Old LCSH term | Current form
-- | --
Blacks—Relations with Indians | Black people ǂx Relations with Indians
Whites—Relations with Indians | White people ǂx Relations with Indians


</body>

</html>

I'll add "people" to the [spreadsheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jFsLExGilXWmXEikliuYUtdipF5HnRbNMZn-rgJYflY/edit#gid=1600276075), is that okay?
Thanks!
Minjie

Sure - changing those two subject headings should be relatively easy. 

I'm working on a ticket to follow up on the subject headings that are not left matching but should probably included the added subject heading.
@minjiec - see https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/issues/1889 as a follow-up. Does it seem reasonable to go forward with the code for now as-is, and then prioritize the linked ticket separately?

Max, first, thank you for planning on working out a solution for those subdivisions!

Second, I have a curve ball for you. In column D "Left match" there are four values -

> 600 - personal name
> 610 - corporate body
> 650 - topical term
> 651 - strings that start with a geographical name

I think we have taken care of LCSH matching 650 fields very well. I wonder how other types of strings are matched. They are definitely in the numerical minority. If I have to choose, I think it'll be desirable to include 651 at least. Here is an example.
The string "Québec (Province)—History—Native Crisis, 1990" would be cataloged in the 651 field. As you can see from the staff view of the bib record [99125157701106421](https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99125157701106421/staff_view)

Would you have a quick solution for matching vocabulary up with bib fields other than 650 as well? Please let don't hesitate to let me know if I can provide more explanation.

Minjie

comments.body:
Failure in the special collections role was from the molecule-mariadb dependency:
```
  TASK [molecule_mariadb : common software] **************************************
  fatal: [instance]: FAILED! => {"changed": false, "msg": "No package matching 'python3-pymysql' is available"}
```
The package does exist when I SSH onto a server. Best guess is that the VM is not using python 3? Since the molecule-mariadb role is only for testing, I've tried rolling back to `python-pymysql`.

heya @hackartisan we have an [nginxplus](https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/nginxplus/defaults/main.yml#L17) role which has a flag that allows us to install the opensource version. We also have a [passenger](https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/tree/main/roles/passenger) one that installs the nginx version that Ubuntu packaging. There's no reason we could think of to maintain -yet another- nginx role.
